article.description: Stephon Marbury shot just 3-for-12 Monday night, but he flipped in a leaning 13-footer under intense defense with a half-second to play to give the Phoenix Suns an 89-88 victory over the Seattle SuperSonics.
article.headline: Marbury improbably does in Sonics this time
article.linkText: Not again?! Sonics lose on last-second prayer
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Stephon Marbury loves to take game-winning shots, and his latest defied the odds. Marbury shot just 3-for-12 Monday night, but he flipped in a leaning 13-footer under intense defense with a half-second to play to give the Phoenix Suns an 89-88 victory over the Seattle SuperSonics. "That is by far the toughest shot I've ever made to win a game,'' Marbury said, "and I've made a lot of game-winning shots.'' After a timeout, the Sonics had one last chance to win. Brent Barry threw a perfect inbounds lob from halfcourt to the basket for Desmond Mason, but Shawn Marion blocked the shot as the buzzer sounded. The Sonics hollered for either a foul or goaltending but got neither. "I think any other time of the game it would have been a foul, but it's the last play of the game,'' Mason said. "They're going to let you play, which is the way it's supposed to be. But from the goaltending standpoint, I thought I got the ball up on the glass before he hit it. It was close.'' Marion said the Sonics would have won if he hadn't gotten a piece of Mason's shot. "I timed it just right,'' Marion said. "That was a perfect lob for him. If I didn't slam it against the backboard, that would have been a dunk for him.'' Marbury's tough shot over Mason capped a tight fourth quarter in which neither team led by more than two points. Rashard Lewis had scored inside on a one-on-one mismatch with Marbury to put Seattle up 88-87 with 11.1 seconds to play. It was the fourth consecutive close loss for the Sonics, and the third straight time they were beaten by a game-winner with less than 2 seconds to play. "They keep fighting, and they keep fighting and they keep fighting,'' Seattle coach Nate McMillan said of his players. "We're just not getting any breaks. You can't play much better defense than we did on that last possession.'' Marbury said the play was called for Marion, but he was covered. Marbury drove to the line, then tossed up what Desmond called "a finger roll from almost the free throw line.'' "Santa came early,'' Marbury said. "It was amazing.'' Phoenix won its third in a row and seventh out of eight to climb six games above .500 for the first time since the end of the 2000-01 season. The Suns have won five in a row at home. Marion had 30 points and 11 rebounds, while Penny Hardaway matched his season high with 20 points. Lewis had 24 points and Predrag Drobnjak 21 for the Sonics, who have lost four in a row and six of seven. The Suns, the second-worst 3-point shooting team in the NBA, were 12-of-26 from 3-point range. Marion made his first five shots, three of them 3-pointers, and scored the Suns' first 13 points as Phoenix shot to a 24-8 lead. But the Sonics switched to a zone defense and closed the gap in the second quarter, using a 9-0 spurt to go ahead 46-45 on Drobnjak's three-point play with 2:18 left in the half. Marion's 15-footer with 24.3 seconds left gave Phoenix a 51-50 halftime lead.

Game notes
Marbury had 12 assists. ... Seattle fell to 9-9 on the road. ... Drobnjak's career high was 23 points at Cleveland Dec. 16. ... Phoenix is 12-3 at home. ... Marion is averaging 25 points in Phoenix's 7-1 run.
